<h3>ABSTRACT</h3>

<p> It’s no secret that mobile technology affects every aspect of our lives. In the modern world almost everyone owns at least a cellphone that connects to the internet. Everyone uses these devices constantly and it’s not difficult to see why – the convenience of being able to do anything anywhere is too appealing to pass up. The most surprising development, however, is the effect this has had on the gaming industry in recent years. While games have been present on mobile phones since they first began to have screens, developers never imagined the impact of mobile technology as a platform until smartphones broke the scene. Since then, games have only become more and more available and varied as mobile technology has. It has shockingly become an important economic resource and created and entirely new market for gaming as a whole. What’s even more surprising is how the gaming itself impacts our lives, including but not limited to how we interact and even how we learn. As humans we inherently enjoy the concept and activity of play. Mobile gaming branches out to not only appeal to our desire to play, but to enable us to learn valuable skills in new ways. It affects our lives in unforeseen ways and can be greatly beneficial to our society as a whole.</p>


<h3> INTRODUCTION </h3>
<p> Gaming has long been considered a niche hobby, made for specific kinds of people with specific kinds of interests. Before mobile gaming popularized the ‘casual game’ most video games were for people willing to put in time and effort into buying consoles or the right kind of computer. The best-selling games also required a whole checklist of qualifications to be considered ‘good’, including up to date graphics, storytelling, user interface, mechanics, etc. Ten years ago it didn’t appear that mobile gaming would ever move beyond the simple games that came preloaded on one’s phone. It certainly wasn’t predicted to be a booming multi-billion dollar industry by 2014 (Feijoo). Now mobile technology as a gaming platform competes as one of the most popular in the gaming industry. The idea of what it is to be a gamer playing a video game is drastically changing and has begun to include almost anyone who owns a smartphone (ESA). The accessibility and convenience of the platform transforms time otherwise spent idling into semi-productive states of learning. Mobile games fill in the gaps of time we otherwise spend waiting, such as at the bus stop or the dentist. Most people are now gamers in some way. It touches our lives in ways never thought possible before the boom of mobile technology. Mobile gaming transformed into its own sub-industry, creating new opportunities for economics, development, learning, medicine, and social interaction. While gaming in general has in the past been lauded as a new way to teach and interact with the world, mobile gaming can finally realize that directive. While in the past not everyone was a gamer, most people today are at least mobile gamers. </p>

<h3>TECH AND DEVELOPMENT</h3>
<p> Mobile gaming has created an entirely new market for enterprising developers to find their start or even freelancers looking to make some money on the side (ESA). Smartphones strike the balance between the mobility and convenience of a cellphone and the computing power of a desktop computer. People literally hold small computers in their hands, even if they don’t think of them that way. The size does restrict some things, like memory, but emerging technologies contribute so much to gaming capabilities that developers have a plethora of tools to work from when designing their games (Soh). Every generation of smartphone brings something new to the table; e.g. the iPhone’s gyroscope which first enabled players to tilt their devices and actually affect gameplay. The newest advancements include updated graphics and processors to better emulate the power of full-sized computers (Forbes). While many may not consider games a particularly good motivator to better technology, the industry’s prevalence in the mobile market has produced some surprising results. </p>


