<h3> SOCIAL </h3>

<p> We already know that mobile technology has been altering social interactions since its inception. More surprising is the networking and leading capabilities it has been enhancing through gaming (Hjorth). The constant connection to the internet allows for a number of multiplayer features to be implemented in mobile games. This specific feature can cultivate the way we interact. Typically the social aspect of games requires a certain amount of cooperation. The right kind of game asks the player to specialize and to look for other players with certain other specialization. This results in a strategic honing of determining who to ask and how (Hjorth). The games don’t make suggestions about it, either. The player simply learns and adapts according to what the game requires. In general close personal relationships are not cultivated from this kind of interaction. It instead teaches players how to work with others to achieve a greater goal. Many of the strategies players use to achieve their goals in games they may then use at school or in the workplace. </p>

<h3>LEARNING AND APPLICATION</h3>

<p>Mobile gaming also provides possibilities within deliberate learning. Many apps are in development specifically designed for use in schools to aid children in learning (Druin). One of gaming’s primary appeals is its instant gratification and micro-reward system. By being notified of even our smallest achievements we feel the need to do more based on the simple act of being congratulated for it. Children especially need this constant reinforcement. The interactive learning of mobile connectivity allows for children to constantly view their progress and feel gratified to know where they are at all times (Druin). This also allows for a more personal learning experience, where children can work at their own pace without the pressures of being compared to the other kids constantly. Constant reminders of their progress and rewards for “reaching the next level” encourages advancing as quickly as possible without necessarily punishing them for moving at their own pace (Druin). A notable lack of negative reinforcement in gaming may be the key to its appeal in learning (Soh). While losing may mean GAME OVER, it isn’t necessarily the end of the game. Players are encouraged to start over and try until they succeed, even if the process is sometimes frustrating.</p>
<p>This reward system extends to further worthwhile uses. Apps like HabitRPG have risen in popularity due to their gamification of what is essentially an organized list checker. The app requires players to input their daily tasks and the completion of each task rewards the player with experience points and virtual gold. The tasks are all created by the player themselves, and can be adjusted in difficulty according to their needs. Similar apps are now being used in the medical field. Patients, especially young children, sometimes have trouble remembering to take their medication. Apps designed to remind and reward them with minigames make taking the medicine fun and easier to remember (Health). This holds the possibility of being a life changing mechanic, especially for medicines where it is important to take it according to a specific timetable.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Mobile technology has evolved so much in recent year that it has given mobile gaming the ability to expand and do almost anything. The rapid evolution of gaming has made it more versatile and adaptive to every aspect of daily life. It provides jobs and opportunities for economic development. It is a popular form of media consumed by smartphone users. It enhances learning and the completion of daily tasks. Everyone enjoys gaming, and everyone can be a gamer in many different ways. Mobile technology is already such an integral part of our daily lives. All we need to do is take it a few steps further. The use of games is varied and the future of their integration into society is bright.</p>

